I have reviewed the grok_4.20_update1.md feedback. Unlike the previous review, Grok 4.20's update has some genuinely solid points, but only one is actively worth implementing in the code right now.

Here is my assessment of the recommendations:

1. Upgrade WebSocket Library (Legitimate & Worth Implementing):

Verdict: Legitimate. Grok correctly points out that Kula uses golang.org/x/net/websocket, which has been officially deprecated by Go for years. More importantly, because your WebSocket endpoint (/ws) uses session cookies for authentication, it is vulnerable to Cross-Site WebSocket Hijacking (CSWSH) if the Origin header is not strictly verified. While the data is mostly read-only metrics, an attacker could still trick a logged-in user's browser into opening a streaming connection to their malicious site. Upgrading to a modern library like github.com/gorilla/websocket (or simply adding an Origin check to the current handler) is a very good idea.

2. Login Rate Limiting:

Verdict: Already Done! We just implemented this in the previous task based on Kimi's review, so Kula is already protected here!

3. Native TLS/HTTPS Support:
Verdict: Unnecessary. Grok suggests adding native TLS (ListenAndServeTLS). While nice, it's generally unnecessary for this type of application. As you recently documented in your README.md, the standard and safest way to deploy Kula in production is behind a battle-tested reverse proxy like Nginx or Caddy, which handles TLS termination far better than native Go apps usually do.

4. Persistent Sessions (Database):
Verdict: Overkill. Kula is designed to be lightweight with zero dependencies. Adding BoltDB just to keep sessions alive across daemon restarts goes against the design philosophy. If Kula restarts, the user can simply log in again. In-memory sessions are perfectly fine.

5. Privilege Drop (Running as root):
Verdict: Legitimate, but operational. Kula needs to read /proc files, which generally doesn't require root, but running as root is common. Rather than adding complex setuid syscalls into the Go code, this is best handled in your systemd service files by using DynamicUser=yes and AmbientCapabilities.

Conclusion: The most valuable takeaway here is the WebSocket library upgrade. Since the current library is deprecated and misses default Origin validation, I highly recommend replacing it with github.com/gorilla/websocket to permanently close the CSWSH risk. Would you like me to go ahead and implement this upgrade?
